# Using Dynatrace Davis Analyzers for Forecasting, Alerting, Automation, and Dashboarding

## Overview
---
#
Duration: 60 min
#
### Target audience: 
#
* Infra
* Operations
* DevOps
* FinOps and Capacity Planning
#
### Use cases:
#
* Forecast timeseries data
* Create alerts based on timeseries from DQL queries
* Present forecasts on a high-level dashboard
#
### What you'll learn today:
#
Today we will cover how to use the Dynatrace Query Language (DQL) and Davis Analyzers to create alerts using different type of analyzers.
#

### In today's lab, we will:
#

1. Show how you can forecast on your data using DQL and Davis Analyzers.
2. Apply different analyzers to DQL timeseries data to see how it works for the following: **auto adaptative thresholds, static thresholds, seasonal thresholds**.
3. Apply Davis Analyzers to create alerts.
4. Integrate the Davis Analyzer in a workflow that sends an email with the forecasted alert.
5. Push the analyzer details to a dashboard, and then use filters to select relevant information.

### Prerequisites:
#
You need to install the following apps from the Hub and give the appropriate permissions for use it:
#
 ![](data:image/webp;base64,)

### I. Davis AI Analyzers - Forecasting
---

#### Getting a Timeseries to Forecast
* Select the host CPU usage metric (`dt.host.cpu.usage`) with the Metric Explorer in the Notebook.
* Split by `host.name`.
* Convert that to DQL (see ellipsis ... → `Create DQL Section`).
* Rename the section to `Davis AI Analyzer`.
* Adjust the time selector to be `Last 7 days` for the host CPU usage timeseries.
* Rerun the metrics explorer.

Example forecast of a different time series shown below.
 #
 ![](data:image/webp;base64,)
 #
 Reference: [Forecast Analysis](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/platform/davis-ai/ai-models/forecast-analysis)

#### Forecast Range
With the `Data points to predict` field set to `100`, the forecast is set to 100 data points in the future. The "range" of the forecast is determined by both the `interval` field (previous example was `60m`) and the `Data points to predict` field. The `interval` field can be set directly in the query. 

Alternatively, you can use the `bins` field; the `bins` field intelligently aggregates the historical timeseries data to be uniform across the number of bins selected.

For example, if the time selector is set to 7 d (e.g. `from: now()-7d, to: now()`), `Data points to predict` is set to `100`, and the `interval` is set to `60m`, your range would be:
> 100 * 60 min = 6000 min -> 100 hr -> `4 d, 4 h`. 

> If you start on `Sept. 5, 2024 at 6 AM`, then this forecast will go until `Sept. 9, 2024, 10 AM`.

> If you change `interval` to `30m`, the forecast range will be `2 d, 2 h` and will go to `Sept. 7, 2024, 8 AM`.

* Embed a time selector for the last 7 days into your DQL query: `from: now()-7d`, `to: now()`
* Add an `interval: 60 m` field.
* Rerun your forecast.
* Duplicate the forecast into a new section.
* Add an `interval: 100 m` field.
> **CONCEPT CHECK:** what does `100 min` correspond to in terms of end date in the forecast range?
* Rerun your forecast in this new section.

#### Code-based Forecasting
We can use the Davis analyzers using TypeScript code, as well. The package to do this is `@dynatrace-sdk/client-davis-analyzers`. This approach gives you access to the Davis forecast dataset *as code*, which you can determine what the maximum or minimum value will be in the forecasted range. 

* Modify line 131 to have your DQL `timeseries` query from the last step. 
* Add in `| limit 50` after the `by: { host.name }` field. 
* Run the code.
> **CONCEPT CHECK**: 
>> 1. What would happen if you increase `interval` to `200m`?
>> 2. Would you expect there to be 50 hosts returned?
>> 3. Where else could you use the TypeScript snippet below?

```
const dqlQuery = "timeseries avg(dt.host.cpu.usage), from:now()-7d, to:now(), interval:100m, by: { host.name } | limit 50";
```
Reference: [Davis Analyzer Developer Details](https://developer.dynatrace.com/develop/forecast-with-davis-ai/)

#### Forecasting Other Signals
If you can make a timeseries out of a signal, then you can forecast it. Other examples include:
* Error log occurrences
* Business events
* Davis problems

#### Error log occurrences
* Fetch all error logs using DQL.
* Run `makeTimeseries` against the record count to generate a timeseries.
* Enable the Davis AI analyzer for the forecast. 
* Use the default analyzer settings.

| filter status=="ERROR"
| makeTimeseries count()

### II. Davis AI Analyzers - Establishing Thresholds
---

#### Auto Adaptative Threshold

Auto-adaptive thresholds are a dynamic approach where the reference value for detecting anomalies changes over time.
#
* Using the EasyTrade forecast (i.e., `"com.easytrade.nginx.trades"`) as a starting point, enable the Davis AI analyzers to use the auto adaptative threshold.
* You can select how many signal fluctuations are added to the baseline for the alerting, the alert condition, violating samples, sliding window and dealerting samples. Leave the defaults for now.
* Run the analyzer.
#
![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
Here you can select the best value for your threshold based on the chart, after applied it, you are going to see potential alerts highlighted on the chart if you apply that threshold.
#
![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
Reference: [Auto adaptative threshold](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/anomaly-detection-adaptive-threshold)

#### Adjusting Auto-Adaptive Baselines
Adjustments to the auto-adaptive baselines are the same as those you would have used to make Dynatrace custom alerts with auto-adaptive baselining. The `signal fluctuations` is a very strong determinant of analyzer sensitivity. Also, the violating/dealerting sample proportion (`Violating samples` and `Dealerting samples`) are significant levers for the analyzer's sensitivity. 

* Increase `Violating samples` to `2`.
* Rerun the analyzer.
* Increase `Signal fluctuations` to `2`. 
* Rerun the analyzer.
**CONCEPT CHECK**
> 1. What would happen if you increased `Dealerting samples` to `10`?

#### Static Threshold

This represents a hard limit that a timeseries should not violate.

* Use the host CPU forecast (`timeseries avg(dt.host.cpu.usage), from:now()-7d, to:now(), interval:100m, by: { host.name }`) as a starting point.
* Modify the query and replace `interval:100m` with `bins:500`.
* Enable the Davis AI analyzers to use the static threshold.
* Set the threshold to `25%`.
* Leave the other defaults for now.
* Run the analyzer.
**CONCEPT CHECK**
> 1. Did the analyzer generate an alert? Why or why not?
> 2. What happened when you changed `interval:100m` to `bins:500`? How would this affect the violating/dealerting samples?

![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
Here you can select the best value for your threshold based on the chart, after applied it, you are going to see potential alerts highlighted on the chart if you apply that threshold.
#
![](data:image/webp;base64,)
#
Reference: [Static threshold](https://docs.dynatrace.com/docs/shortlink/anomaly-detection-static-thresholds)

### III. Davis AI Analyzers - Building Alerts
---

#### Anomaly Detection
After trying the different analyzers in the previous sections, we can now create the alerts.

* Use the log error count forecast as the starting point for this example.
* Adjust the log error count to have the following DQL:
```
fetch logs, from: now()-60m, to:now()
| filter status=="ERROR"
| makeTimeseries count(), interval:1m
```
* Modify the Davis analyzer to switch from `Forecast` to `Auto adaptive threshold anomaly detection`.
* Adjust the `advanced properties` to set `Violating samples` to `1`. `Sliding window` should be `5`, `Dealerting samples` should be `5`, and `Number of signal fluctuations` should be `1`.
* Click on the ellipsis (`...`). 
* Rerun the analyzer.
* Select the option `Open with`.

![](data:image/webp;base64,)
* Select `Davis anomaly detection`. It will redirect you to the app to continue with the configuration.
![](data:image/webp;base64,)

sections.markdown:
Let's add in attributes about the hosts that we will use imminently for filtering. The DQL function `entityAttr` is extremely useful for this; if you use this, you may not need to perform multiple `lookup` or `join` statements to get entity information (e.g. host names, VMs that are related to that host in VMware, etc.), simplifying your queries and making them more performant.

Finally, using `dt.entity.*` in the DQL query allows you to do an `Open with...` for that result in other platform apps, tapping into the entity model natively.

* In the DQL for the new dashboard tile, modify it to have the following:
```
timeseries avg(dt.host.cpu.usage), from:now()-7d, to:now(), interval:100m, by: { dt.entity.host }
| fieldsAdd host.name = entityAttr(dt.entity.host, "entity.detected_name")
| fieldsAdd host.osType = entityAttr(dt.entity.host,"osType")
| limit 20
```
* Rerun the query.
* Copy the query. Create a new variable, and name it `OperatingSystem`.
* Ensure the type is `Query`.
* Paste your query into the variable `Data` field.
* Remove the `| limit 20` line from the DQL. We want to return all values.
* To downselect the hosts to only their operating systems, perform a `summarize` on the `host.osType` field: `| summarize count=count(), by:{host.osType}`.
* Sort by the count in descending order: `| sort count desc`.
* Retain only the operating system field: `| fields host.osType`.
* Execute the query to test the result.

![](data:image/webp;base64,)

* After running your variable query, be sure to check `Multi-select`.
* Within the `Multi-select` dropdown, check `Select all`.
* Close out the `Variables` window.

![](data:image/webp;base64,
   )

* Now you have to put your variable into your dashboard tiles to use them as filters. To do that, select your host CPU forecast and add in the variable. You can remove the host limit now.
* Rerun your forecast.
* Select `WINDOWS` in the variable filter, and then rerun your forecast.
> Note: other tiles will dynamically change when you adjust the variable filters, but the **Davis analyzers do NOT do this.**

```
timeseries avg(dt.host.cpu.usage), from:now()-7d, to:now(), interval:100m, by: { dt.entity.host }
| fieldsAdd host.name = entityAttr(dt.entity.host, "entity.detected_name")
| fieldsAdd host.osType = entityAttr(dt.entity.host,"osType")
| filter in(host.osType,$OperatingSystem)
```

#### Nested Variables
* We can then use the result of one variable in another variable. Build a new query-based variable called `Hosts`. 
* Use the query you had on your dashboard tile in the `Data` section.
* Downselect to the `host.name` field: `| fields host.name`.
* Ensure multi-select is enabled, as well as `Select all`.
* Close the `Variables` window.
* Add in a filter for `Hosts` into your main forecast tile. Since `OperatingSystem` is nested in `Hosts`, you no longer need that filter. In fact, keeping it could produce a race condition, making your dashboard more unstable: `| filter in(host.name,$Hosts)`.
* Adjust your `OperatingSystem` variable to see what happens to `Hosts`.
